                <note rend="inline" type="source">124.93/91</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Acting Chief of the Division of Far Eastern
                        Affairs, Department of State</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-07-31">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 31, 1924</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. Butler Wright telephoned me today stating that Signor Rosso of the Italian
                    Embassy had today informed him that the Embassy had received information from
                    Rome to the effect that the Italian Government had decided not to raise its
                    Legation at Peking to the rank of an Embassy, and that the decision had been
                    arrived at for reasons of economy. Mr. Wright suggested that this information be
                    made of record in order that it might be considered in connection with the
                    general question of raising the American Legation at Peking to an Embassy.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>F. P. L[<hi rend="smallcaps">ockhart</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
